Tom,<br><br>
You stated, &quot; If we truly believe that, then how important are any acts of contrition? By anyone? Should they matter?<br><br>
The answer in my mind is no.  I don't need anything from others to find my inner peace.  For us it is simple.  For others it is not simple.  Their expectations were to go to war and be a hero or at the very least the returning warrior whom everyone appreciated.  There was no fanfare when we left so why should we expect it when we returned?  We were conditioned by history, which was a school requirement.  All wars this nation fought returned their men home with honor whether they expected it or not.  Those who accepted the standard exhibited by this nation were disappointed in its performance.<br>
There was hatred by many for the combat veteran.  Something to be despised spit on.   The press gave them visibility because they were from the same Liberal mindset.  The media drew the lines and those who helped them make it newsworthy.  The public in the normal fashion begins to agree with the press and away we go.  It happens today on other matters.  We just weren't fashionable.  They had a commitment.  They had attacked the war and the sadistic warrior for 10 years.  Consistence was required.  Use the veteran as the society scapegoat and cleans the soul of the perpetrators. <br><br>
&quot;Allow me to ask a rhetorical question. Is it ok for returning vets to spit on those whom they claimed spit on them? Check out thread #20. I just did last nite. I give up.<br><br>
Tom you use the word claimed.  I doubt if a vet would miss the fact they were spit on and I for one will not doubt the validity of the statement.  Should a vet spit on those who DID spit on them?  Spitting on a man  in the Tennessee land you love would get his butt kicked if he was lucky and killed if not.  You didn't spit on a man, mess with his family, call him a liar, and believe it or not mess with his dog.  All were met with swift action.  I wouldn't spit on a man who spit on me I would do worse.  Religion has never asked a man to trivialize his honor.  Remember the word tolerance is not absolute.<br><br>
There will always be a rift between those who cannot respect each other.  Remember it wasn't the soldier who spit on those who were welcoming him home.<br><br>
Once again I say the warrior only needs to accept him or herself.  The conflict arises in the multitude of variations of acceptance needs.  The protestors and the spitting group don't give a damn.  If we self-destruct they have achieved their goal.  Reduced us to the lowest denominator that spitting denotes.  Spitting is only one of the methods used to exhibit this social placement of the warrior.<br><br>
&quot;The answer lies in vets supporting other vets, yet the most sublime state of mind is for us to be generous. I think that we all have the capability.&quot;  Possibly.<br><br>
Coexistence is achievable, but forgiveness may be one of those unachievable goals at least for me.  Apathy versus empathy.<br><br>
Peace<br><br>

